I was tired of having to waste quite a bit of space to store the cardboard box I was using as a lightbox, so I designed something better. The lightbox folds up into a compact form, allowing for easy storage and locks into place when folded closed. It even has a carrying handle.  
Enjoy.

All you need are a few shorter M3 screws (I used 14mm length), 2 Long M3's (50mm), a few 1/2inch wood screws to attach to the dowels, 2 sheets of 1/4 inch ply/MDF/other ect material in whatever rectangular dimensions you'd like, and 5 cut 1/2inch diameter dowels, 4 of which act as the hinged arms and one of which acts as the handle. title: Mission Control >> Temperature Monitor for extruder motor and print bed (etc)

description.text:
Monitor your extruder motor, ready to react if it starts to go over temp (options: panic, turn on a fan, vow to install an extruder fan). Similarly monitor your print bed (edges of my prints tend to warp if someone turns on the air conditioner and the room goes below 25 Celcius). The thermometer probes are housed in probe holders (snap on) and secured to your motor/ print bed with double-sided tape. No fuss or screws needed. The thermometer read-out panels are mounted onto holders (with a snug snap-on fit) that can swivel on a mounted base, to adjust viewing angles; avoiding glare/ reflections. This set up works on any printer, although the base for the thermometer holder is designed to mount on the Y-Axis arm of the Printrbot-Simple Metal. You could easily draw up a rod to make a stand or mount it anywhere your imagination takes you (dimensions: 5mm (W) x 7mm (H) rod with 2.8mm (dia) holes). The two holder panels provided are labelled - "EXT(ruder) Drive" and "Print Bed". If you need a holder labelled differently, drop me a comment and I'll be happy to customise it for you. I did think of throwing one more probe inside the Printrbot body but that has not given me any temperature-related problems so far... BOM:

2 x M3 8mm or 12mm screws (to secure panel holders onto base)
Digital thermometer probes (I bought mine here for under USD2 each: http://www.aliexpress.com/item/Digital-LCD-Probe-Fridge-Freezer-Thermometer-Thermograph-for-Refrigerator-110C-Black-White/936092083.html)
Double-sided tape (heavy duty, no real need for heat resistant type)
Cable wrap (optional)

This is a german "Panzerjaeger-Triebwagen" from WWII and a kind of weird project. Lacking any modell railroad i decided to build something that runs on the Lego tracks. At ebay i got a flatbed railroad car and constructed the historic "Panzerzug" to match.
I have no clue what scale it is but 2 Lego mini figures fit (barely) inside it. The hull consists of two identically and rotationally symmetric parts plus the top of the cabin. Originally i planned to glue the main parts together, but with the cabin roof on top it fits and holds quite firm and nicely. Printed with a 0.5mm nozzle on my OrdBot with something like 35 degree support the bridging was challenging but worked quite well. I think its possible even without support. The little PzIV turrets demanded some testing before they fit and turned the way i wanted it. It depends on shrinking plastic and calibration of the printer.
The turrets need some 2.5mm sticks for the barrels. If you have real 200 by 200 mm printbed or even a bit larger, you can try to combine the two hull parts and print them as one. My print room was slightly off center and unwilling to print all corners, so i split it in half.

title: Denon AH-D1100 Headphones - Earcup brackets with screw-less locking mechanism

description.text: These expensive headphones reproduces very nice bass tones with very detailed highs. Unfortunately, earcup brackets are designed/produced with very bad plastic construction. My colleague's one was broken while he was listening to music. I decided to make him happy again by 3D printing a much robust construction.

• Reading STL files to Slicer:

    • import Denon_AHD1100_headphones_earcup_fork_right.stl and place it on the bed as is. This will be right side earcup bracket.
    • import the same file second time or copy the previous object, mirror on X-axis.
    • import Denon_AHD1100_headphones_earcup_fork_lock.stl and place it 2 or more (spare) on the bed.

  • Support generation:

    • Add support bars under two ends (4.5mm pins which would go into earcup sidewall holes) of each earcup bracket.
    • Add support to the middle of the 4mm hole into which metal pin of head-rest would go in.

  • Slicer/Printer settings:

    • 1.75mm PLA filament, black (fits better than gray/silver)
    • 220C nozzle temperature
    • 60C bed temperature
    • 0.15mm 1st layer height
    • 0.1 ~ 0.2 mm layer height (depending on the quality you desire)
    • 0.8mm vertical shell (2 loops with 0.4mm nozzle diameter)
    • 0.8mm horizontal shell (top/bottom, 8 loops @ 0.1mm layer height)
    • 15~20% inner fill density
    • 20mm/sec or less printing speed (perimeter, loops, everywhere)
  • Print
    • 4m filament
    • 4h printing time (with 0.1mm layer height)
    • Enjoy!

description.text: This is a replacement front body mount for the Audi R8 LMS bodies for Kyosho Mini-Z RC models. You need to print the body holder with support structure in order for the print to turn out good as there is a part of the body holder that is in the air. You can vary the infill percentage, but even with the default settings the part should be strong enough, no need to go to maximum infill percentage. We recommend to use 0.1mm layer height for best results, though you might experiment with not so fine resolutions as well.

This is for the Ultimaker challenge. FWIW, challenge wise, I'm a maintainer of MCAD and a meta-maintainer of github.com/SolidCode. I'm also THE RepRap/RepLab evangelist here in Finland ;) Anyway, on to interesting stuff:
I've refactored the code, making the parametrization better, and added a roll holder so that a label roll can sit inside the dispenser. Currently the size of the roll is limited somewhat, I intend to refactor some more to make allowances for bigger rolls. Support for packing tape might come too. A handle is planned, and I have some vague ideas to mechanize it, in the spirit of packing tape dipensers. If anyone can link pics of the inner workings of one, it would be useful ;) Update: Added a guard that should keep the roll in. Handle might be coming next... Update2: Refactored the code so that now it can be adapted for bigger rolls automatically, see image. I'm mostly pleased with the code now. Update3: Added a handle! description.text:
Another take on a cable clip.
This thing has an interior that mimics a USB port to hold any extra cables while you're not using them.
Due to the placement of my laptop on my desk (far left, thing-o-matic on the right, and writing space in between) I can only use one side of its USB ports without interfering with my writing space. Any extra cables used to fall to the floor when not in use, and I would have to spend horrible fractions of a calorie, and precious seconds to pick it up and switch it in. Now this is no longer an issue as I have the cables right beside each other!

Print with the face down to make sure the interior fits well. Mine printed fine the first try with stock thing-o-matic settings and an MK6 stepper extruder, but you may need to adjust your settings, scale it slightly or change the solidworks file, depending on your setup.
I used industrial velcro tape to attach it to the desk, though you could probably design something if your desk has any place to attach it. I've also been meaning to make a versions with puzzle pieces for the left, right and both sides to allow them to string together, but I haven't had the time recently to play with sizing for parts to snap together well.

Phone case for HTC sense and iPhone 5.  
Print your own flexible elephant phone case with a sturdy trunk for angled position and big floppy ears to protect your phone. Original concept and design was made by my twelve year old daughter Bente as part of an after school project. We designed two cases, one suitable for an HTC sense and one for an iphone 5. I think the case will also work for an iPhone 5s, but did not test it.  
The design was made in Fusion 360 and printed on an Ultimaker Original+.

Print suggestions:
  • For the case two STL files can be downloaded, one for an HTC sense and one for the iPhone 5.
  • The trunk and button are suitable for both cases (two STL files).
  • The case should be printed with flexible PLA. I used Ultimaker PLA flexible white. For the Ultimaker Original+ these settings were used: heated bed switched off and covered with blue tape, printing speed at 10 mm/s, temperature at 230 degrees, a few drops of sewing machine oil in the bowden tube to avoid jamming.
  • For the trunk and button I used Colorfabb PLA traffic red (iphone case) and some obscure glow-in-the-dark PLA for the HTC sense case. Printing at 50 mm/s, nozzle at 190 degrees and heated bed at 50 degrees.
